## Backend (C)

### New endpoints — all `DEFINE_AUTH_ROUTE` (run as user)

| Method | Path | Handler | Description |
|--------|------|---------|-------------|
| `GET` | `/trash/list` | `handle_trash_list_impl` | List trashed items (name, original path, deleted_at, type, size) |
| `POST` | `/trash/restore` | `handle_trash_restore_impl` | Restore item (body: `{"name":"..."}`) — moves back to original path |
| `DELETE` | `/trash/:name` | `handle_trash_delete_impl` | Permanently delete one trashed item |
| `DELETE` | `/trash` | `handle_trash_empty_impl` | Empty entire trash |

Note: No separate "trash an item" endpoint needed — the existing `DELETE /fs/file` and `DELETE /fs/dir` are modified to move to trash instead of hard-deleting. They call `trash_item(path)` from `trash.c` internally.

### Files to modify/create

**`src/fs/trash.c`** (new) — all 5 handler implementations:
- `handle_trash_list_impl`: scan `~/.imaginary/trash/files/`, read each `.info` sidecar, return JSON array
- `trash_item(const char *path)` (internal helper, called from `fs.c` delete handlers):
  1. Validate path with `safe_path()`
  2. Ensure `~/.imaginary/trash/{files,info}` dirs exist (`mkdir -p` style)
  3. Handle name collisions (append `.1`, `.2`, etc.)
  4. `rename()` file/dir into `trash/files/<name>`
  5. Write `trash/info/<name>.info` with original path + ISO timestamp
  6. Returns 0 on success, -1 on error (sets errno)
- `handle_trash_restore_impl`:
  1. Read `.info` to get original path
  2. Ensure parent directory of original path exists
  3. `rename()` from `trash/files/<name>` back to original path
  4. `unlink()` the `.info` file
- `handle_trash_delete_impl`: `unlink()` file + `.info` from trash. For dirs: recursive delete using `nftw()` with `FTW_DEPTH` flag (files first, then dirs)
- `handle_trash_empty_impl`: iterate and remove all entries in `trash/files/` (recursive for dirs) and `trash/info/`

**`src/fs/trash.h`** (new) — handler declarations

**`src/fs/fs.c`** — Modify `handle_fs_delete_file_impl` and `handle_fs_rmdir_impl` to move to trash instead of hard-deleting. Both call `trash_item(path)` from `trash.c`. Directories are trashed as a whole unit (the entire tree moves into `trash/files/` as one entry). `rename()` handles this atomically since it's the same filesystem.

**`src/main.c`** — Register the 4 new trash routes with `DEFINE_AUTH_ROUTE` + `CHTTP_*` macros (list, restore, delete one, empty)

**`Makefile`** — `src/fs/trash.c` will be picked up automatically by the existing `SOURCES := $(shell find src/ lib/ vendor/ -name '*.c')` pattern (verify this).

### Key implementation details
- All trash operations run as the authenticated user (via `fork_and_run`), so file permissions are naturally enforced
- Paths in `.info` files are relative to user's home (same as all other fs operations)
- `rename()` works for both files and directories (same filesystem guaranteed since trash is in home dir)
- For recursive directory deletion in permanent delete: implement a simple `nftw()` or manual recursive `opendir`/`unlink`/`rmdir`

